// The tube reliability problem
// ENIAC (1945): 17,468 vacuum tubes
// Tube failure rate: ~1 per 2 days
// MTBF (system): ~7 minutes between failures
// 
// Bell System (1947):
// Tubes in service: ~10 million
// Replacement cost: $100M+ per year

// Surface states explained
// Silicon crystal: atoms bonded in lattice
// At surface: bonds have nothing to connect to
// Result: 'dangling bonds' trap electrons
// 
// Solution 1: Electrolyte (temporary)
// Solution 2: Point contact (Brattain)
// Solution 3: Oxide layer (future: MOSFET)

// First transistor performance
// Contact spacing: ~50 micrometers
// Voltage gain: ~15
// Current gain: ~100  
// Power gain: ~18
// Frequency: Audio range only
// 
// Compare to vacuum triode:
// Power gain: ~100
// Frequency: MHz range
// 
// Transistor wins: No heater, no vacuum

// Transistor evolution
// 1947: Point-contact (Bardeen/Brattain)
//       ‚Üí Unreliable, noisy
// 1948: Junction transistor (Shockley)
//       ‚Üí Reliable, manufacturable
// 1959: MOSFET (Kahng/Atalla)
//       ‚Üí Field effect finally works!
// Today: FinFET, GAA-FET
//       ‚Üí Advanced field-effect designs

// Lilienfeld's 1926 FET concept
// Gate: Metal electrode
// Insulator: Thin film (air or oxide)
// Channel: Copper sulfide semiconductor
// 
// Problem: Impure materials
// Cu2S purity: ~95% (needed: 99.999%)
// Surface states: Uncontrolled
// Result: No measurable field effect
// 
// Same concept works in 1959:
// Gate: Aluminum
// Insulator: Silicon dioxide (SiO2)
// Channel: Pure silicon (99.9999%)

// First transistor specifications
// Germanium base: n-type, high purity
// Contacts: Gold foil on plastic wedge
// Spacing: ~50 micrometers
// Gain: ~100 (current amplification)
// 
// Compare to vacuum tube:
// Tube: 5W power, 10cm¬≥ volume
// Transistor: 0.05W, 1mm¬≥

// The Tyranny of Numbers
// Components: Transistors, resistors, capacitors
// Connections: 2-4 per component
// Failure rate per joint: 0.001%
// 
// System with 10,000 components:
// Joints: ~30,000
// Expected failures: 300/year
// MTBF: ~1 day

// Semiconductor components
// Resistor: R = œÅL/A (doped region)
// Capacitor: C = ŒµA/d (junction)
// Transistor: NPN or PNP junctions
// 
// All from the same material!
// Germanium (Kilby) or Silicon (Noyce)

// Planar vs. Mesa transistor
// Mesa: Etch away surrounding material
//       - Fragile, exposed junctions
//       - Hard to interconnect
// 
// Planar: Grow oxide on surface
//       - Protected, stable
//       - Metal traces on oxide
//       - Basis of ALL modern ICs

// Kilby's first IC (1958)
// Material: Germanium
// Components: 1 transistor, 3 resistors, 1 capacitor
// Interconnects: Gold wire bonds (external)
// Function: Phase-shift oscillator
// Size: ~11 √ó 1.5 mm
// 
// Limitations:
// - Wire bonds add failure points
// - Germanium hard to oxidize
// - Mesa transistors fragile

// Noyce's planar IC (1959)
// Material: Silicon
// Interconnects: Aluminum on SiO2
// Process: Planar (Hoerni invention)
// 
// Key innovations:
// 1. Thermal oxide for passivation
// 2. Oxide windows for contacts
// 3. Metal traces on oxide surface
// 4. All processing from one side
// 
// This is how ALL modern ICs are made

// IC fabrication steps (simplified)
// 1. Start with p-type silicon wafer
// 2. Grow thermal oxide (SiO2)
// 3. Pattern and etch oxide (photolithography)
// 4. Diffuse n-type dopant (transistor regions)
// 5. Grow thin gate oxide
// 6. Deposit and pattern aluminum
// 7. Passivation (protective oxide)
// 8. Bond pads for external connections

// Apollo Guidance Computer specs
// Memory: 36,864 words (ROM) + 2,048 words (RAM)
// Word size: 15 bits + parity
// Speed: ~43,000 adds/second
// Weight: 70 lbs
// Power: 55 watts
// ICs: 4,100 (3-input NOR gates)
// Reliability required: 99.9% for 2-week mission

// IC reliability bathtub curve
// 
// Failure |\
// Rate    | \      /
//         |  \----/
//         |   Useful life
//         +---------------> Time
//         ^ Burn-in removes
//           infant mortality

// NOR-based logic
// NOT A    = A NOR A
// A AND B  = (A NOR A) NOR (B NOR B)
// A OR B   = (A NOR B) NOR (A NOR B)
// 
// AGC used ~5,000 NOR gates total
// Each IC contained 3-input NOR gates
// Resistor-Transistor Logic (RTL)

// AGC priority scheduling
// P66 (landing): Highest priority
// P63 (guidance): High priority
// Radar update: Lower priority
// 
// When overloaded:
// - Shed lowest priority tasks
// - Restart when capacity available
// - Never lose critical functions

// Busicom's original design
// Chip 1: Keyboard controller
// Chip 2: Display driver
// Chip 3: BCD adder
// Chip 4: Multiplier
// ... 8 more chips
// Total: 12 custom ICs
// Design time: 12-18 months
// Cost: Very high

// Intel 4004 instruction set highlights
// 
// Arithmetic:
// ADD R  - Add register to A
// SUB R  - Subtract register from A
// INC R  - Increment register
// DAA    - Decimal adjust (BCD correction)
// 
// Control:
// JMP    - Unconditional jump (12-bit address)
// JCN    - Conditional jump
// JMS    - Jump to subroutine (uses stack)
// BBL    - Branch back and load (return)
// 
// 46 total instructions

// Architecture lineage
// 
// 4004 (1971): BCD calculator
//   ‚Üí Dead end (calculator niche)
// 
// 8008 (1972): Terminal controller
//   ‚Üí 8080 (1974): General purpose
//   ‚Üí 8086 (1978): 16-bit extension
//   ‚Üí 80386 (1985): 32-bit
//   ‚Üí x86-64 (2003): 64-bit
//   ‚Üí YOUR PC TODAY
// 
// Every Intel PC traces to Datapoint 2200

// Intel 4004 key specs
// Data bus: 4 bits
// Address space: 4KB ROM, 640 bytes RAM
// Registers: 16 √ó 4-bit (general purpose)
// Stack: 3-level hardware stack
// Clock: 740 kHz
// Transistors: 2,300
// 
// Your Micro4 targets:
// Data: 4 bits
// Memory: 256 bytes
// Registers: 1 accumulator
// Instructions: ~16
